---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Dwarf galaxies";
import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Dwarf galaxies</h1>

    <p>
      <strong>Dwarf galaxies</strong> are low-mass galaxies with stellar masses M* ≲ 10^9–10^10 M_☉. They are the most abundant galaxy population in the universe and are sensitive probes of galaxy formation physics, including baryonic feedback, environmental quenching, and the nature of dark matter.
    </p>

    <h2>Importance for galaxy evolution</h2>
    <p>
      Dwarf galaxies constrain models of:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Reionization (dwarf galaxies as early sources of ionizing photons)</li>
      <li>Baryonic feedback (supernova-driven winds, AGN feedback at low masses)</li>
      <li>Environmental quenching (ram pressure stripping, tidal effects in groups/clusters)</li>
      <li>Dark matter profiles (observed vs. predicted velocity curves)</li>
      <li>Galaxy formation timescales (star formation histories)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Challenges in dwarf galaxy studies</h2>
    <p>
      Dwarf galaxies are intrinsically faint and distant; spectroscopic follow-up is limited in large surveys. As a result, most dwarfs discovered by upcoming wide-field surveys (LSST, Euclid) will be characterized primarily via broadband photometry.
    </p>
    <p>
      Watkins et al. (2026) demonstrate that morphological parameters derived from photometry alone (isophotal shapes, concentration, asymmetry, smoothness) show limited discriminatory power among dwarf classes, suggesting that multi-wavelength and high-dimensional statistical approaches are necessary to parse dwarf evolutionary pathways.
    </p>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li id="ref1">Watkins A. E., et al. (2026). "Isophote shape analysis and the unfortunate subtlety of dwarf galaxy structure." arXiv:2603.11166. See paper page: <a href="/pages/watkins_2026_isophote_dwarf_structure">Watkins et al. (2026)</a>.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
